# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: developer-experience
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Productivity is a crucial factor in the production performance of firms and nations.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Increasing national productivity can raise living standards because wage growth improves people's ability to purchase goods and services, enjoy leisure, improve housing, and education and contribute to social and environmental programs.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Productivity growth can also help businesses to be more profitable.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Productivity measures that use one class of inputs or factors, but not multiple factors, are called partial productivities.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In practice, measurement in production means measures of partial productivity.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Interpreted correctly, these components are indicative of productivity development, and approximate the efficiency with which inputs are used in an economy to produce goods and services.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] However, productivity is only measured partially – or approximately.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In a way, the measurements are defective because they do not measure everything, but it is possible to interpret correctly the results of partial productivity and to benefit from them in practical situations.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] At the company level, typical partial productivity measures are such things as worker hours, materials or energy used per unit of production.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Before the widespread use of computer networks, partial productivity was tracked in tabular form and with hand-drawn graphs.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Tabulating machines for data processing began being widely used in the 1920s and 1930s and remained in use until mainframe computers became widespread in the late 1960s through the 1970s.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] By the late 1970s inexpensive computers allowed industrial operations to perform process control and track productivity.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Today data collection is largely computerized and almost any variable can be viewed graphically in real time or retrieved for selected time periods.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In macroeconomics, a common partial productivity measure is labour productivity.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Labour productivity is a revealing indicator of several economic indicators as it offers a dynamic measure of economic growth, competitiveness, and living standards within an economy.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] It is the measure of labour productivity (and all that this measure takes into account) which helps explain the principal economic foundations that are necessary for both economic growth and social development.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In general labour productivity is equal to the ratio between a measure of output volume (gross domestic product or gross value added) and a measure of input use (the total number of hours worked or total employment).
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The output measure is typically net output, more specifically the value added by the process under consideration, i.e. the value of outputs minus the value of intermediate inputs.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] This is done in order to avoid double-counting when an output of one firm is used as an input by another in the same measurement.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In macroeconomics the most well-known and used measure of value-added is the gross domestic product or GDP.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Increases in it are widely used as a measure of the economic growth of nations and industries.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] GDP is the income available for paying capital costs, labor compensation, taxes and profits.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Some economists instead use gross value added (GVA); there is normally a strong correlation between GDP and GVA.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The measure of input use reflects the time, effort and skills of the workforce.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The denominator of the ratio of labour productivity, the input measure is the most important factor that influences the measure of labour productivity.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Labour input is measured either by the total number of hours worked of all persons employed or total employment (head count).
[src:developer-experience/productivity] There are both advantages and disadvantages associated with the different input measures that are used in the calculation of labour productivity.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] However, the quality of hours-worked estimates is not always clear.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In particular, statistical establishment and household surveys are difficult to use because of their varying quality of hours-worked estimates and their varying degree of international comparability.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] GDP per capita is a very rough measure of average living standards or economic well-being and is one of the core indicators of economic performance.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Maximizing GDP, in principle, also allows maximizing capital usage.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] For this reason, GDP is systematically biased in favour of capital intensive production at the expense of knowledge and labour-intensive production.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The use of capital in the GDP-measure is considered to be as valuable as the production's ability to pay taxes, profits and labor compensation.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The bias of the GDP is actually the difference between the GDP and the producer income.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Another labour productivity measure, output per worker, is often seen as a proper measure of labour productivity, as here: "Productivity isn't everything, but in the long run it is almost everything.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] When multiple inputs are considered, the measure is called multi-factor productivity or MFP and is typically estimated using growth accounting.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] If the inputs specifically are labor and capital, and the outputs are value added intermediate outputs, the measure is called total factor productivity (TFP].
[src:developer-experience/productivity] TFP measures the residual growth that cannot be explained by the rate of change in the services of labour and capital.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] MFP replaced the term TFP used in the earlier literature, and both terms continue in use (usually interchangeably).
[src:developer-experience/productivity] TFP is often interpreted as a rough average measure of productivity, more specifically the contribution to economic growth made by factors such as technical and organisational innovation.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The most famous description is that of Robert Solow's (1957): "I am using the phrase 'technical change' as a shorthand expression for any kind of shift in the production function.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In practice, TFP is "a measure of our ignorance", as Abramovitz (1956) put it, precisely because it is a residual.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] This ignorance covers many components, some wanted (like the effects of technical and organizational innovation), others unwanted (measurement error, omitted variables, aggregation bias, model misspecification) Hence the relationship between TFP and productivity remains unclear.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] When all outputs and inputs are included in the productivity measure it is called total productivity.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] A valid measurement of total productivity necessitates considering all production inputs.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] If we omit an input in productivity (or income accounting) this means that the omitted input can be used unlimitedly in production without any impact on accounting results.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Because total productivity includes all production inputs, it is used as an integrated variable when we want to explain income formation of the production process.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Davis has considered the phenomenon of productivity, measurement of productivity, distribution of productivity gains, and how to measure such gains.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] He refers to an article suggesting that the measurement of productivity shall be developed so that it "will indicate increases or decreases in the productivity of the company and also the distribution of the 'fruits of production' among all parties at interest".
[src:developer-experience/productivity] According to Davis, the price system is a mechanism through which productivity gains are distributed, and besides the business enterprise, receiving parties may consist of its customers, staff and the suppliers of production inputs.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In the main article is presented the role of total productivity as a variable when explaining how income formation of production is always a balance between income generation and income distribution.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The income change created by production function is always distributed to the stakeholders as economic values within the review period.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Productivity growth is a crucial source of growth in living standards.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Productivity growth means more value is added in production and this means more income is available to be distributed.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Recent discussions of productivity have expanded to include behavioral approaches to habit formation.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] According to author James Clear, "Habits are the compound interest of self-improvement," emphasizing that consistent small actions lead to long-term efficiency and results.This perspective connects productivity to psychology and everyday behavior rather than time management alone.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Productivity growth is important to the firm because it means that it can meet its (perhaps growing) obligations to workers, shareholders, and governments (taxes and regulation), and still remain competitive or even improve its competitiveness in the market place.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Adding more inputs will not increase the income earned per unit of input (unless there are increasing returns to scale).
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In fact, it is likely to mean lower average wages and lower rates of profit.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] But, when there is productivity growth, even the existing commitment of resources generates more output and income.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Income generated per unit of input increases.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Additional resources are also attracted into production and can be profitably employed.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In the most immediate sense, productivity is determined by the available technology or know-how for converting resources into outputs, and the way in which resources are organized to produce goods and services.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Historically, productivity has improved through evolution as processes with poor productivity performance are replaced with newer processes.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Process improvements may include organizational structures (e.g. core functions and supplier relationships), management systems, work arrangements, manufacturing techniques, and changing market structure.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] A famous example is the assembly line and the process of mass production that appeared in the decade following commercial introduction of the automobile.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Mass production dramatically reduced the labor in producing parts for and assembling the automobile, but after its widespread adoption productivity gains in automobile production were much lower.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] A similar pattern was observed with electrification, which saw the highest productivity gains in the early decades after introduction.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Many other industries show similar patterns.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The pattern was again followed by the computer, information and communications industries in the late 1990s when much of the national productivity gains occurred in these industries.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] There is a general understanding of the main determinants or drivers of productivity growth.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Certain factors are critical for determining productivity growth.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The Office for National Statistics (UK) identifies five drivers that interact to underlie long-term productivity performance: investment, innovation, skills, enterprise and competition.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Research and development (R&D) tends to increase productivity growth, with public R&D showing larger spillovers and smaller firms experiencing larger productivity gains from public R&D.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] See also list of countries by productivity growth.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Technology has enabled massive personal productivity gains.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Use of computers, spreadsheets, email, and other technological advances have made it possible for a knowledge worker to seemingly produce more in a day than was previously possible in a year.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Environmental factors such as sleep and leisure play a significant role in work productivity and received wage.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Productivity is influenced by effective supervision and job satisfaction.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] An effective or knowledgeable supervisor (for example a supervisor who uses the Management by objectives method) has an easier time motivating their employees to produce more in quantity and quality.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] An employee who has an effective supervisor, motivating them to be more productive is likely to experience a new level of job satisfaction thereby becoming a driver of productivity itself.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] There is also considerable evidence to support improved productivity through operant conditioning reinforcement, successful gamification engagement, and research-based recommendations on principles and implementation guidelines for using monetary rewards effectively.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Workplace bullying results in a loss of productivity, as measured by self-rated job performance.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Over time, targets of bullying will spend more time protecting themselves against harassment by bullies and less time fulfilling their duties.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Workplace incivility has also been associated with diminished productivity in terms of quality and quantity of work.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] A toxic workplace is a workplace that is marked by significant drama and infighting, where personal battles often harm productivity.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] While employees are distracted by this, they cannot devote time and attention to the achievement of business goals.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] When toxic employees leave the workplace, it can improve the culture overall because the remaining staff become more engaged and productive.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The presence of a workplace psychopath may have a serious detrimental impact on productivity in an organisation.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In companies where the traditional hierarchy has been removed in favor of an egalitarian, team-based setup, the employees are often happier, and individual productivity is improved (as they themselves are better placed to increase the efficiency of the workfloor).
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Companies that have these hierarchies removed and have their employees work more in teams are called liberated companies or "Freedom Inc.'s".
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The Kaizen system of bottom-up, continuous improvement was first practiced by Japanese manufacturers after World War II, most notably as part of The Toyota Way.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Productivity is one of the main concerns of business management and engineering.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Many companies have formal programs for continuously improving productivity, such as a production assurance program.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Whether they have a formal program or not, companies are constantly looking for ways to improve quality, reduce downtime and inputs of labor, materials, energy and purchased services.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Often simple changes to operating methods or processes increase productivity, but the biggest gains are normally from adopting new technologies, which may require capital expenditures for new equipment, computers or software.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Modern productivity science owes much to formal investigations that are associated with scientific management.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In office buildings and service-centred companies, productivity is largely influenced and affected by operational byproducts—meetings.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The past few years have seen a positive uptick in the number of software solutions focused on improving office productivity.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In truth, proper planning and procedures are more likely to help than anything else.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Overall productivity growth in the US was relatively slow from the 1970s through the early 1990s, and again from the 2000s to 2020s.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Although several possible causes for the slowdown have been proposed there is no consensus.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The matter is subject to a continuing debate that has grown beyond questioning whether just computers can significantly increase productivity to whether the potential to increase productivity is becoming exhausted.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] In order to measure the productivity of a nation or an industry, it is necessary to operationalize the same concept of productivity as in a production unit or a company, yet, the object of modelling is substantially wider and the information more aggregate.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The calculations of productivity of a nation or an industry are based on the time series of the SNA, System of National Accounts.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] National accounting is a system based on the recommendations of the UN (SNA 93) to measure the total production and total income of a nation and how they are used.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] International or national productivity growth stems from a complex interaction of factors.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Some of the most important immediate factors include technological change, organizational change, industry restructuring and resource reallocation, as well as economies of scale and scope.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] A nation's average productivity level can also be affected by the movement of resources from low-productivity to high-productivity industries and activities.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Over time, other factors such as research and development and innovative effort, the development of human capital through education, and incentives from stronger competition promote the search for productivity improvements and the ability to achieve them.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Ultimately, many policy, institutional and cultural factors determine a nation's success in improving productivity.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] At the national level, productivity growth raises living standards because more real income improves people's ability to purchase goods and services (whether they are necessities or luxuries), enjoy leisure, improve housing and education and contribute to social and environmental programs.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Some have suggested that the UK's 'productivity puzzle' is an urgent issue for policy makers and businesses to address in order to sustain growth.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Over long periods of time, small differences in rates of productivity growth compound, like interest in a bank account, and can make an enormous difference to a society's prosperity.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Nothing contributes more to reduction of poverty, to increases in leisure, and to the country's ability to finance education, public health, environment and the arts'.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] Productivity is considered basic statistical information for many international comparisons and country performance assessments and there is strong interest in comparing them internationally.
[src:developer-experience/productivity] The OECD publishes an annual Compendium of Productivity Indicators that includes both labor and multi-factor measures of productivity.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] A **programmer**, **computer programmer** or **coder** is an author of computer source code – someone with skill in computer programming.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] The professional titles *software developer* and *software engineer* may be used for jobs that require a programmer.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Sometimes a programmer or job position is identified by the language used or target platform.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] For example, assembly programmer, web developer.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] The job titles that include programming tasks have differing connotations across the computer industry and to different individuals.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] A *software developer* primarily implements software based on specifications and fixes bugs.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Other duties may include reviewing code changes and testing.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] To achieve the required skills for the job, they might obtain a computer science or associate degree, attend a programming boot camp or be self-taught.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Sometimes, a software engineer is required to have a degree in software engineering, computer engineering, or computer science.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Some countries legally require an engineering degree to be called *engineer*.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] British countess and mathematician Ada Lovelace is often considered to be the first computer programmer.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] She authored an algorithm, which was published in October 1842, for calculating Bernoulli numbers on the Charles Babbage analytical engine.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Because the machine was not completed in her lifetime, she never experienced the algorithm in action.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] In 1941, German civil engineer Konrad Zuse was the first person to execute a program on a working, program-controlled, electronic computer.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] From 1943 to 1945, per computer scientist Wolfgang K.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Giloi and AI professor Raúl Rojas et al., Zuse created the first, high-level programming language, Plankalkül.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Members of the 1945 ENIAC programming team of Kay McNulty, Betty Jennings, Betty Snyder, Marlyn Wescoff, Fran Bilas and Ruth Lichterman have since been credited as the first professional computer programmers.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] The first company founded specifically to provide software products and services was the Computer Usage Company in 1955.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Before that time, computers were programmed either by customers or the few commercial computer manufacturers of the time, such as Sperry Rand and IBM.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] The software industry expanded in the early 1960s, almost immediately after computers were first sold in mass-produced quantities.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Universities, governments, and businesses created a demand for software.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Many of these programs were written in-house by full-time staff programmers; some were distributed between users of a particular machine for no charge, while others were sold on a commercial basis.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Other firms, such as Computer Sciences Corporation (founded in 1959), also started to grow.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Computer manufacturers soon started bundling operating systems, system software and programming environments with their machines; the IBM 1620 came with the 1620 Symbolic Programming System and FORTRAN.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] The industry expanded greatly with the rise of the personal computer (PC) in the mid-1970s, which brought computing to the average office worker.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] In the following years, the PC also helped create a constantly growing market for games, applications and utility software.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] This resulted in increased demand for software developers for that period of time.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Computer programmers write, test, debug, and maintain the detailed instructions, called computer programs, that computers must follow to perform their functions.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Programmers also conceive, design, and test logical structures for solving problems by computer.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Many technical innovations in programming — advanced computing technologies and sophisticated new languages and programming tools — have redefined the role of a programmer and elevated much of the programming work done today.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Job titles and descriptions may vary, depending on the organization.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Programmers work in many settings, including corporate information technology (IT) departments, big software companies, small service firms and government entities of all sizes.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Many professional programmers also work for consulting companies at client sites as contractors.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Licensing is not typically required to work as a programmer, although professional certifications are commonly held by programmers.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Programming editors, also known as source code editors, are text editors that are specifically designed for programmers or developers to write the source code of an application or a program.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Most of these editors include features useful for programmers, which may include color syntax highlighting, auto indentation, auto-complete, bracket matching, syntax check, and allows plug-ins.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] These features aid the users during coding, debugging and testing.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] According to BBC News, 17% of computer science students could not find work in their field six months after graduation in 2009 which was the highest rate of the university subjects surveyed while 0% of medical students were unemployed in the same survey.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] After the crash of the dot-com bubble (1999–2001) and the Great Recession (2008), many U.S. programmers were left without work or with lower wages.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] The current prediction for 2024 to 2034 is a decline of -6 percent.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Since computer programming can be done from anywhere in the world, companies sometimes hire programmers in countries where wages are lower.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] If domestic demand has increased, it is mainly to replace the attrition of aging programmers or those leaving this occupation.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] However, for software developers BLS projects current growth at 15% that is down from their prediction from 2019 to 2029 of a 22% increase in employment, from 1,469,200 to 1,785,200 jobs with a median base salary of $110,000 per year.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] This prediction is lower than the earlier 2010 to 2020 predicted increase of 30% for software developers.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Though the distinction is somewhat ambiguous, software developers engage in a wider array of aspects of application development and are generally higher skilled than programmers, making outsourcing less of a risk.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Another reason for the decline for programmers is their skills are being merged with other professions, such as developers, as employers increase the requirements for a position over time (i.e. full-stack developer).
[src:developer-experience/programmer] This skill consolidation has led some employers to claim there is a skills shortage with regard to programming talent.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] However, US programmers and unions counter that some are exaggerating their case in order to obtain programmers from countries with lower wages and avoid paying for training in very specific technologies.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Then there is the additional concern that recent advances in artificial intelligence and vibe coding might drastically impact the demand for future generations of Software professions.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] As of 2024 in Japan, the demand for programmers is increasing rapidly due mainly to the aging demographics of their workforce and their low birth rate not being sufficient for replacement has led to more use of AI to help fill the gap.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Programming education involves the teaching and learning of computer programming concepts, languages, and practices.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] It is offered through various formats, including formal computer science degree programs, vocational training, career and technical education centers, coding bootcamps, libraries, online courses, and self-directed learning.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Educational initiatives often focus on problem-solving, computational thinking, logical thinking, and the development of algorithms.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] In primary and secondary education, programming is increasingly integrated into computer literacy curricula through initiatives such as Hour of Code, Code Club, Learn to Code, and by getting computers in the classroom.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] At the higher education level, programming instruction may include coursework in software engineering, data structures, debugging, software design, and specialized domains such as game development, artificial intelligence, cryptography, or data science.
[src:developer-experience/programmer] Numerous platforms and resources like AI chat bots, educational programming software, and online integrated development environments have expanded access to programming education.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] A **software development process** prescribes a process for developing software.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] It typically divides an overall effort into smaller steps or sub-processes that are intended to ensure high-quality results.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The process may describe specific deliverables – artifacts to be created and completed.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Although not strictly limited to it, software development process often refers to the high-level process that governs the development of a software system from its beginning to its end of life – known as a methodology, model or framework.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The system development life cycle (SDLC) describes the typical phases that a development effort goes through from the beginning to the end of life for a system – including a software system.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] A methodology prescribes how engineers go about their work in order to move the system through its life cycle.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] A methodology is a classification of processes or a blueprint for a process that is devised for the SDLC.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] For example, many processes can be classified as a spiral model.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Software process and software quality are closely interrelated; some unexpected facets and effects have been observed in practice.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The SDLC drives the definition of a methodology in that a methodology must address the phases of the SDLC.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Generally, a methodology is designed to result in a high-quality system that meets or exceeds expectations (requirements) and is delivered on time and within budget even though computer systems can be complex and integrate disparate components.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Various methodologies have been devised, including waterfall, spiral, agile, rapid prototyping, incremental, and synchronize and stabilize.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] A major difference between methodologies is the degree to which the phases are sequential vs. iterative.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Agile methodologies, such as XP and scrum, focus on lightweight processes that allow for rapid changes.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Iterative methodologies, such as Rational Unified Process and dynamic systems development method, focus on stabilizing project scope and iteratively expanding or improving products.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Sequential or big-design-up-front (BDUF) models, such as waterfall, focus on complete and correct planning to guide larger projects and limit risks to successful and predictable results.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Anamorphic development is guided by project scope and adaptive iterations.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] In scrum, for example, one could say a single user story goes through all the phases of the SDLC within a two-week sprint.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] By contrast the waterfall methodology, where every business requirement is translated into feature/functional descriptions which are then all implemented typically over a period of months or longer.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] A project can include both a project life cycle (PLC) and an SDLC, which describe different activities.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] According to Taylor (2004), "the project life cycle encompasses all the activities of the project, while the systems development life cycle focuses on realizing the product requirements".
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The term *SDLC* is often used as an abbreviated version of *SDLC methodology*.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Further, some use *SDLC* and *traditional SDLC* to mean the waterfall methodology.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] According to Elliott (2004), SDLC "originated in the 1960s, to develop large scale functional business systems in an age of large scale business conglomerates.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Information systems activities revolved around heavy data processing and number crunching routines".
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The structured systems analysis and design method (SSADM) was produced for the UK government Office of Government Commerce in the 1980s.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Ever since, according to Elliott (2004), "the traditional life cycle approaches to systems development have been increasingly replaced with alternative approaches and frameworks, which attempted to overcome some of the inherent deficiencies of the traditional SDLC".
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Since DSDM in 1994, all of the methodologies on the above list except RUP have been agile methodologies - yet many organizations, especially governments, still use pre-agile processes (often waterfall or similar).
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The following are notable methodologies somewhat ordered by popularity.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Agile software development refers to a group of frameworks based on iterative development, where requirements and solutions evolve via collaboration between self-organizing cross-functional teams.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The term was coined in the year 2001 when the Agile Manifesto was formulated.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The waterfall model is a sequential development approach, in which development flows one way (like a waterfall) through the SDLC phases.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] In 1988, Barry Boehm published a software system development spiral model, which combines key aspects of the waterfall model and rapid prototyping, in an effort to combine advantages of top-down and bottom-up concepts.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] It emphases a key area many felt had been neglected by other methodologies: deliberate iterative risk analysis, particularly suited to large-scale complex systems.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Various methods combine linear and iterative methodologies, with the primary objective of reducing inherent project risk by breaking a project into smaller segments and providing more ease-of-change during the development process.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Software prototyping is about creating prototypes, i.e. incomplete versions of the software program being developed.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Rapid application development (RAD) is a methodology which favors iterative development and the rapid construction of prototypes instead of large amounts of up-front planning.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The "planning" of software developed using RAD is interleaved with writing the software itself.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The lack of extensive pre-planning generally allows software to be written much faster and makes it easier to change requirements.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Shape Up is a software development approach introduced by Basecamp in 2018.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] It is a set of principles and techniques that Basecamp developed internally to overcome the problem of projects dragging on with no clear end.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Its primary target audience is remote teams.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Shape Up has no estimation and velocity tracking, backlogs, or sprints, unlike waterfall, agile, or scrum.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Instead, those concepts are replaced with appetite, betting, and cycles.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] As of 2022, besides Basecamp, notable organizations that have adopted Shape Up include UserVoice and Block.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Chaos model has one main rule: always resolve the most important issue first.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Incremental funding methodology - an iterative approach.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Lightweight methodology - a general term for methods that only have a few rules and practices.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Structured systems analysis and design method - a specific version of waterfall.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] As part of the larger slow movement, emphasizes careful and gradual work without (or minimal) time pressures.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Slow programming aims to avoid bugs and overly quick release schedules.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] V-Model (software development) - an extension of the waterfall model.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Unified Process (UP) is an iterative software development methodology framework, based on Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] UP organizes the development of software into four phases, each consisting of one or more executable iterations of the software at that stage of development: inception, elaboration, construction, and guidelines.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The waterfall model describes the SDLC phases such that each builds on the result of the previous one.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Not every project requires that the phases be sequential.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] For relatively simple projects, phases may be combined or overlapping.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Alternative methodologies to waterfall are described and compared below.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Some process models are abstract descriptions for evaluating, comparing, and improving the specific process adopted by an organization.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 12207 is the international standard describing the method to select, implement, and monitor the life cycle for software.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] The Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI) is one of the leading models and is based on best practices.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Independent assessments grade organizations on how well they follow their defined processes, not on the quality of those processes or the software produced.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] ISO 9000 describes standards for a formally organized process to manufacture a product and the methods of managing and monitoring progress.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Although the standard was originally created for the manufacturing sector, ISO 9000 standards have been applied to software development as well.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Like CMMI, certification with ISO 9000 does not guarantee the quality of the end result, only that formalized business processes have been followed.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 15504 *Information technology—Process assessment*, a.k.a.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Software Process Improvement Capability Determination (SPICE), is a framework for the assessment of software processes.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] This standard is aimed at setting out a clear model for process comparison.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] It models processes to manage, control, guide, and monitor software development.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] This model is then used to measure what a development organization or project team actually does during software development.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] This information is analyzed to identify weaknesses and drive improvement.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] It also identifies strengths that can be continued or integrated into common practice for that organization or team.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] ISO/IEC 24744 *Software Engineering—Metamodel for Development Methodologies*, is a power type-based metamodel for software development methodologies.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Soft systems methodology is a general method for improving management processes.
[src:developer-experience/software-development-process] Method engineering is a general method for improving information system processes.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Software development involves many skills and job specializations, including programming, testing, documentation, graphic design, user support, marketing, and fundraising.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Common types of tools are compilers, integrated development environments (IDEs), and version control.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The details of the process used for a development effort vary.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The process may be confined to a formal, documented standard, or it can be customized and emergent for the development effort.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The process may be sequential, in which each major phase (i.e., design, implement, and test) is completed before the next begins, but an iterative approach—where small aspects are separately designed, implemented, and tested—can reduce risk and cost and increase quality.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Each of the available methodologies is best suited to specific kinds of projects, based on various technical, organizational, project, and team considerations.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Another focus in many programming methodologies is the idea of trying to catch issues such as security vulnerabilities and bugs as early as possible (shift-left testing) to reduce the cost of tracking and fixing them.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] In 2009, it was estimated that 32% of software projects were delivered on time and on budget, and with full functionality.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] An additional 44% were delivered, but were missing at least one of their features.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The remaining 24% were cancelled before release.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Software development life cycle describes the typical phases of the process of developing software.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The sources of ideas for software products are plentiful.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] These ideas can come from market research, including the demographics of potential new customers, existing customers, sales prospects who rejected the product, other internal software development staff, or a creative third party.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Ideas for software products are usually first evaluated by marketing personnel for economic feasibility, fit with existing channels of distribution, possible effects on existing product lines, required features, and fit with the company's marketing objectives.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] In the marketing evaluation phase, the cost and time assumptions are evaluated.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The feasibility analysis estimates the project's return on investment, its development cost and its timeframe.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Based on this analysis, the company can make a business decision to invest in further development.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] After deciding to develop the software, the company is focused on delivering the product at or below the estimated cost and time and with a high standard of quality (i.e., lack of bugs) and the desired functionality.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Nevertheless, most software projects run late, and sometimes compromises are made in features or quality to meet a deadline.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Software analysis begins with a requirements analysis to capture the business needs of the software.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Challenges for the identification of needs are that current or potential users may have different and incompatible needs, may not understand their own needs, and change their needs during the process of software development.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Ultimately, the result of analysis is a detailed specification for the product that developers can work from.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Software analysts often decompose the project into smaller objects, components that can be reused for increased cost-effectiveness, efficiency, and reliability.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Decomposing the project may enable a multi-threaded implementation that runs significantly faster on multiprocessor computers.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] During the analysis and design phases of software development, structured analysis is often used to break down the customer's requirements into pieces that can be implemented by software programmers.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The underlying logic of the program may be represented in data-flow diagrams, data dictionaries, pseudocode, state transition diagrams, and/or entity relationship diagrams.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] If the project incorporates a piece of legacy software that has not been modeled, this software may be modeled to help ensure it is correctly incorporated with the newer software.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Design involves choices about the implementation of the software, such as which programming languages and database software to use, or how the hardware and network communications will be organized.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Design may be iterative with users consulted about their needs in a process of trial and error.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Design often involves people who are expert in aspects such as database design, screen architecture, and the performance of servers and other hardware.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Designers often attempt to find patterns in the software's functionality to spin off distinct modules that can be reused with object-oriented programming.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] An example of this is the model–view–controller, an interface between a graphical user interface and the backend.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The central feature of software development is creating and understanding the software that implements the desired functionality.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] There are various strategies for writing the code.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Cohesive software has various components that are independent from each other.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Coupling is the interrelation of different software components, which is viewed as undesirable because it increases the difficulty of maintenance.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Often, software programmers do not follow industry best practices, resulting in code that is inefficient, difficult to understand, or lacking documentation on its functionality.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] These standards are especially likely to break down in the presence of deadlines.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] As a result, testing, debugging, and revising the code become much more difficult.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Code refactoring is a technique for restructuring existing code without changing its external behavior, often to improve its design, readability, or maintainability.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Since the popularization of large language models, AI-assisted software development has been used to augment human programming by having an AI handle syntax and write code.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Testing is the process of ensuring that the code executes correctly and without errors.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Debugging is performed by each software developer on their own code to confirm that the code does what it is intended to.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] In particular, it is crucial that the software executes on all inputs, even if the result is incorrect.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Code reviews by other developers are often used to scrutinize new code added to the project, and according to some estimates dramatically reduce the number of bugs persisting after testing is complete.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Once the code has been submitted, quality assurance – a separate department of non-programmers for most large companies – test the accuracy of the entire software product.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Testing activities may also occur throughout the software development life cycle, depending on the methodology used.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Acceptance tests derived from the original software requirements are a popular tool for this.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] When tests are written before the code, this is called test-driven development.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Production is the phase in which software is deployed to the end user.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] During production, the developer may create technical support resources for users or a process for fixing bugs and errors that were not caught earlier.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] There might also be a return to earlier development phases if user needs changed or were misunderstood.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Software development is performed by **software developers**, usually working on a team.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Efficient communications between team members is essential to success.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] This is more easily achieved if the team is small, used to working together, and located near each other.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Communications also help identify problems at an earlier stage of development and avoid duplicated effort.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Many development projects avoid the risk of losing essential knowledge held by only one employee by ensuring that multiple workers are familiar with each component.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Software development involves professionals from various fields, not just software programmers but also product managers who set the strategy and roadmap for the product, individuals specialized in testing, documentation writing, graphic design, user support, marketing, and fundraising.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Although workers for proprietary software are paid, most contributors to open-source software are volunteers.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Alternately, they may be paid by companies whose business model does not involve selling the software, but something else – such as services and modifications to open source software.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Computer-aided software engineering (CASE) is tools for the partial automation of software development.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] CASE enables designers to sketch out the logic of a program, whether one to be written, or an already existing one to help integrate it with new code or reverse engineer it (for example, to change the programming language).
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Documentation comes in two forms that are usually kept separate – one intended for software developers, and another made available to the end user to help them use the software.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Most developer documentation is in the form of code comments for each file, class, and method that cover the application programming interface (API)—how the piece of software can be accessed by another—and often implementation details.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] This documentation is helpful for new developers to understand the project when they begin working on it.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] In agile development, the documentation is often written at the same time as the code.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] User documentation is more frequently written by technical writers.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Accurate estimation is crucial at the feasibility stage and in delivering the product on time and within budget.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The process of generating estimations is often delegated by the project manager.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Because the effort estimation is directly related to the size of the complete application, it is strongly influenced by the addition of features in the requirements—the more requirements, the higher the development cost.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Aspects not related to functionality, such as the experience of the software developers and code reusability, are also essential to consider in estimation.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] As of 2019, most of the tools for estimating the amount of time and resources for software development were designed for conventional applications and are not applicable to web applications or mobile applications.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] An integrated development environment (IDE) supports software development with enhanced features compared to a simple text editor.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] IDEs often include automated compiling, syntax highlighting of errors, debugging assistance, integration with version control, and semi-automation of tests.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Version control is a popular way of managing changes made to the software.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Whenever a new version is checked in, the software saves a backup of all modified files.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] If multiple programmers are working on the software simultaneously, it manages the merging of their code changes.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The software highlights cases where there is a conflict between two sets of changes and allows programmers to fix the conflict.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] A view model is a framework that provides the viewpoints on the system and its environment, to be used in the software development process.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] It is a graphical representation of the underlying semantics of a view.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] The purpose of viewpoints and views is to enable human engineers to comprehend very complex systems and to organize the elements of the problem around domains of expertise.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] In the engineering of physically intensive systems, viewpoints often correspond to capabilities and responsibilities within the engineering organization.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Fitness functions are automated and objective tests to ensure that the new developments do not deviate from the established constraints, checks and compliance controls.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] Intellectual property can be an issue when developers integrate open-source code or libraries into a proprietary product, because most open-source licenses used for software require that modifications be released under the same license.
[src:developer-experience/software-development] As an alternative, developers may choose a proprietary alternative or write their own software module.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The object of use can be a software application, website, book, tool, machine, process, vehicle, or anything a human interacts with.
[src:developer-experience/usability] A usability study may be conducted as a primary job function by a *usability analyst* or as a secondary job function by designers, technical writers, marketing personnel, and others.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It is widely used in consumer electronics, communication, and knowledge transfer objects (such as a cookbook, a document or online help) and mechanical objects such as a door handle or a hammer.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability includes methods of measuring usability, such as needs analysis and the study of the principles behind an object's perceived efficiency or elegance.
[src:developer-experience/usability] In human-computer interaction and computer science, usability studies the elegance and clarity with which the interaction with a computer program or a web site (web usability) is designed.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability considers user satisfaction and utility as quality components, and aims to improve user experience through iterative design.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Complex computer systems find their way into everyday life, and at the same time the market is saturated with competing brands.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This has made usability more popular and widely recognized in recent years, as companies see the benefits of researching and developing their products with user-oriented methods instead of technology-oriented methods.
[src:developer-experience/usability] By understanding and researching the interaction between product and user, the *usability expert* can also provide insight that is unattainable by traditional company-oriented market research.
[src:developer-experience/usability] For example, after observing and interviewing users, the usability expert may identify needed functionality or design flaws that were not anticipated.
[src:developer-experience/usability] A method called *contextual inquiry* does this in the naturally occurring context of the users own environment.
[src:developer-experience/usability] In the user-centered design paradigm, the product is designed with its intended users in mind at all times.
[src:developer-experience/usability] In the user-driven or participatory design paradigm, some of the users become actual or de facto members of the design team.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The term *user friendly* is often used as a synonym for *usable*, though it may also refer to accessibility.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability describes the quality of user experience across websites, software, products, and environments.
[src:developer-experience/usability] There is no consensus about the relation of the terms ergonomics (or human factors) and usability.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Some think of usability as the software specialization of the larger topic of ergonomics.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Others view these topics as tangential, with ergonomics focusing on physiological matters (e.g., turning a door handle) and usability focusing on psychological matters (e.g., recognizing that a door can be opened by turning its handle).
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability is also important in website development (web usability).
[src:developer-experience/usability] According to Jakob Nielsen, "Studies of user behavior on the Web find a low tolerance for difficult designs or slow sites.
[src:developer-experience/usability] And they don't want to learn how to use a home page.
[src:developer-experience/usability] There's no such thing as a training class or a manual for a Web site.
[src:developer-experience/usability] People have to be able to grasp the functioning of the site immediately after scanning the home page—for a few seconds at most." Otherwise, most casual users simply leave the site and browse or shop elsewhere.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability can also include the concept of prototypicality, which is how much a particular thing conforms to the expected shared norm, for instance, in website design, users prefer sites that conform to recognised design norms.
[src:developer-experience/usability] ISO defines usability as "The extent to which a product can be used by specified users to achieve specified goals with effectiveness, efficiency, and satisfaction in a specified context of use." The word "usability" also refers to methods for improving ease-of-use during the design process.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability is often associated with the functionalities of the product (cf.
[src:developer-experience/usability] ISO definition, below), in addition to being solely a characteristic of the user interface (cf. framework of system acceptability, also below, which separates *usefulness* into *usability* and *utility*).
[src:developer-experience/usability] For example, in the context of mainstream consumer products, an automobile lacking a reverse gear could be considered *unusable* according to the former view, and *lacking in utility* according to the latter view.
[src:developer-experience/usability] When evaluating user interfaces for usability, the definition can be as simple as "the perception of a target user of the effectiveness (fit for purpose) and efficiency (work or time required to use) of the Interface".
[src:developer-experience/usability] Each component may be measured subjectively against criteria, e.g., Principles of User Interface Design, to provide a metric, often expressed as a percentage.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It is important to distinguish between usability testing and usability engineering.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability testing is the measurement of ease of use of a product or piece of software.
[src:developer-experience/usability] In contrast, usability engineering (UE) is the research and design process that ensures a product with good usability.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability is a non-functional requirement.
[src:developer-experience/usability] As with other non-functional requirements, usability cannot be directly measured but must be quantified by means of indirect measures or attributes such as, for example, the number of reported problems with ease-of-use of a system.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The term intuitive is often listed as a desirable trait in usable interfaces, sometimes used as a synonym for learnable.
[src:developer-experience/usability] In the past, Jef Raskin discouraged using this term in user interface design, claiming that easy to use interfaces are often easy because of the user's exposure to previous similar systems, thus the term 'familiar' should be preferred.
[src:developer-experience/usability] As an example: Two vertical lines "||" on media player buttons do not intuitively mean "pause"—they do so by convention.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Researchers have also investigated intuitive interaction for older people, people living with dementia, and children.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Some have argued that aiming for "intuitive" interfaces (based on reusing existing skills with interaction systems) could lead designers to discard a better design solution only because it would require a novel approach and to stick with boring designs.
[src:developer-experience/usability] However, applying familiar features into a new interface has been shown not to result in boring design if designers use creative approaches rather than simple copying.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The throwaway remark that "the only intuitive interface is the nipple; everything else is learned." is still occasionally mentioned.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Any breastfeeding mother or lactation consultant will tell you this is inaccurate and the nipple does in fact require learning on both sides.
[src:developer-experience/usability] However, the term intuitive interaction has become well accepted in the research community over the past 20 or so years and, although not perfect, it should probably be accepted and used.
[src:developer-experience/usability] ISO/TR 16982:2002 ("Ergonomics of human-system interaction—Usability methods supporting human-centered design") is an International Standards Organization (ISO) standard that provides information on human-centered usability methods that can be used for design and evaluation.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It details the advantages, disadvantages, and other factors relevant to using each usability method.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It explains the implications of the stage of the life cycle and the individual project characteristics for the selection of usability methods and provides examples of usability methods in context.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The main users of ISO/TR 16982:2002 are project managers.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It therefore addresses technical human factors and ergonomics issues only to the extent necessary to allow managers to understand their relevance and importance in the design process as a whole.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The guidance in ISO/TR 16982:2002 can be tailored for specific design situations by using the lists of issues characterizing the context of use of the product to be delivered.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Selection of appropriate usability methods should also take account of the relevant life-cycle process.
[src:developer-experience/usability] ISO/TR 16982:2002 is restricted to methods that are widely used by usability specialists and project managers.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It does *not* specify the details of how to implement or carry out the usability methods described.
[src:developer-experience/usability] ISO 9241 is a multi-part standard that covers a number of aspects of people working with computers.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Although originally titled *Ergonomic requirements for office work with visual display terminals (VDTs)*, it has been retitled to the more generic *Ergonomics of Human System Interaction*.
[src:developer-experience/usability] As part of this change, ISO is renumbering some parts of the standard so that it can cover more topics, e.g. tactile and haptic interaction.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The first part to be renumbered was part 10 in 2006, now part 110.
[src:developer-experience/usability] IEC 62366-1:2015 + COR1:2016 & IEC/TR 62366-2 provide guidance on usability engineering specific to a medical device.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Any system or device designed for use by people should be easy to use, easy to learn, easy to remember (the instructions), and helpful to users.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The design team should be user-driven and it should be in direct contact with potential users.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Several evaluation methods, including personas, cognitive modeling, inspection, inquiry, prototyping, and testing methods may contribute to understanding potential users and their perceptions of how well the product or process works.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability considerations, such as who the users are and their experience with similar systems must be examined.
[src:developer-experience/usability] As part of understanding users, this knowledge must "...be played against the tasks that the users will be expected to perform." This includes the analysis of what tasks the users will perform, which are most important, and what decisions the users will make while using your system.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Designers must understand how cognitive and emotional characteristics of users will relate to a proposed system.
[src:developer-experience/usability] One way to stress the importance of these issues in the designers' minds is to use personas, which are made-up representative users.
[src:developer-experience/usability] See below for further discussion of personas.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Another more expensive but more insightful method is to have a panel of potential users work closely with the design team from the early stages.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Test the system early on, and test the system on real users using behavioral measurements.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This includes testing the system for both learnability and usability.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It is important in this stage to use quantitative usability specifications such as time and errors to complete tasks and number of users to test, as well as examine performance and attitudes of the users testing the system.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Finally, "reviewing or demonstrating" a system before the user tests it can result in misleading results.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The emphasis of empirical measurement is on measurement, both informal and formal, which can be carried out through a variety of evaluation methods.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Iterative design is a design methodology based on a cyclic process of prototyping, testing, analyzing, and refining a product or process.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Based on the results of testing the most recent iteration of a design, changes and refinements are made.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This process is intended to ultimately improve the quality and functionality of a design.
[src:developer-experience/usability] In iterative design, interaction with the designed system is used as a form of research for informing and evolving a project, as successive versions, or iterations of a design are implemented.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The key requirements for Iterative Design are: identification of required changes, an ability to make changes, and a willingness to make changes.
[src:developer-experience/usability] When a problem is encountered, there is no set method to determine the correct solution.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Rather, there are empirical methods that can be used during system development or after the system is delivered, usually a more inopportune time.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Ultimately, iterative design works towards meeting goals such as making the system user friendly, easy to use, easy to operate, simple, etc.
[src:developer-experience/usability] There are a variety of usability evaluation methods.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Certain methods use data from users, while others rely on usability experts.
[src:developer-experience/usability] There are usability evaluation methods for all stages of design and development, from product definition to final design modifications.
[src:developer-experience/usability] When choosing a method, consider cost, time constraints, and appropriateness.
[src:developer-experience/usability] For a brief overview of methods, see Comparison of usability evaluation methods or continue reading below.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability methods can be further classified into the subcategories below.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Cognitive modeling involves creating a computational model to estimate how long it takes people to perform a given task.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Models are based on psychological principles and experimental studies to determine times for cognitive processing and motor movements.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Cognitive models can be used to improve user interfaces or predict problem errors and pitfalls during the design process.
[src:developer-experience/usability] With parallel design, several people create an initial design from the same set of requirements.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Each person works independently, and when finished, shares concepts with the group.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The design team considers each solution, and each designer uses the best ideas to further improve their own solution.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This process helps generate many different, diverse ideas, and ensures that the best ideas from each design are integrated into the final concept.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This process can be repeated several times until the team is satisfied with the final concept.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Sometimes it is useful to break a task down and analyze each individual aspect separately.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This helps the tester locate specific areas for improvement.
[src:developer-experience/usability] To do this, it is necessary to understand how the human brain processes information.
[src:developer-experience/usability] A model of the human processor is shown below.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Many studies have been done to estimate the cycle times, decay times, and capacities of each of these processors.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Variables that affect these can include subject age, aptitudes, ability, and the surrounding environment.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Long-term memory is believed to have an infinite capacity and decay time.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Keystroke level modeling is essentially a less comprehensive version of GOMS that makes simplifying assumptions in order to reduce calculation time and complexity.
[src:developer-experience/usability] These usability evaluation methods involve observation of users by an experimenter, or the testing and evaluation of a program by an expert reviewer.
[src:developer-experience/usability] They provide more quantitative data as tasks can be timed and recorded.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Card sorting is a way to involve users in grouping information for a website's usability review.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Participants in a card sorting session are asked to organize the content from a Web site in a way that makes sense to them.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Participants review items from a Web site and then group these items into categories.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Card sorting helps to learn how users think about the content and how they would organize the information on the Web site.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Card sorting helps to build the structure for a Web site, decide what to put on the home page, and label the home page categories.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It also helps to ensure that information is organized on the site in a way that is logical to users.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Tree testing is a way to evaluate the effectiveness of a website's top-down organization.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Participants are given "find it" tasks, then asked to drill down through successive text lists of topics and subtopics to find a suitable answer.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Tree testing evaluates the findability and labeling of topics in a site, separate from its navigation controls or visual design.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Ethnographic analysis is derived from anthropology.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Field observations are taken at a site of a possible user, which track the artifacts of work such as Post-It notes, items on desktop, shortcuts, and items in trash bins.
[src:developer-experience/usability] These observations also gather the sequence of work and interruptions that determine the user's typical day.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Heuristic evaluation is a usability engineering method for finding and assessing usability problems in a user interface design as part of an iterative design process.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It involves having a small set of evaluators examining the interface and using recognized usability principles (the "heuristics").
[src:developer-experience/usability] It is the most popular of the usability inspection methods, as it is quick, cheap, and easy.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Heuristic evaluation was developed to aid in the design of computer user-interface design.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It relies on expert reviewers to discover usability problems and then categorize and rate them by a set of principles (heuristics.) It is widely used based on its speed and cost-effectiveness.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Jakob Nielsen's list of ten heuristics is the most commonly used in industry.
[src:developer-experience/usability] These are ten general principles for user interface design.
[src:developer-experience/usability] They are called "heuristics" because they are more in the nature of rules of thumb than specific usability guidelines.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Thus, by determining which guidelines are violated, the usability of a device can be determined.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability inspection is a review of a system based on a set of guidelines.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The review is conducted by a group of experts who are deeply familiar with the concepts of usability in design.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The experts focus on a list of areas in design that have been shown to be troublesome for users.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Pluralistic Inspections are meetings where users, developers, and human factors people meet together to discuss and evaluate step by step of a task scenario.
[src:developer-experience/usability] As more people inspect the scenario for problems, the higher the probability to find problems.
[src:developer-experience/usability] In addition, the more interaction in the team, the faster the usability issues are resolved.
[src:developer-experience/usability] In consistency inspection, expert designers review products or projects to ensure consistency across multiple products to look if it does things in the same way as their own designs.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Activity analysis is a usability method used in preliminary stages of development to get a sense of situation.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It involves an investigator observing users as they work in the field.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Also referred to as user observation, it is useful for specifying user requirements and studying currently used tasks and subtasks.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The data collected are qualitative and useful for defining the problem.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The following usability evaluation methods involve collecting qualitative data from users.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Although the data collected is subjective, it provides valuable information on what the user wants.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Task analysis means learning about users' goals and users' ways of working.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Task analysis can also mean figuring out what more specific tasks users must do to meet those goals and what steps they must take to accomplish those tasks.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Along with user and task analysis, a third analysis is often used: understanding users' environments (physical, social, cultural, and technological environments).
[src:developer-experience/usability] A focus group is a focused discussion where a moderator leads a group of participants through a set of questions on a particular topic.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Although typically used as a marketing tool, focus groups are sometimes used to evaluate usability.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Used in the product definition stage, a group of 6 to 10 users are gathered to discuss what they desire in a product.
[src:developer-experience/usability] An experienced focus group facilitator is hired to guide the discussion to areas of interest for the developers.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Focus groups are typically videotaped to help get verbatim quotes, and clips are often used to summarize opinions.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The data gathered is not usually quantitative, but can help get an idea of a target group's opinion.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Surveys have the advantages of being inexpensive, require no testing equipment, and results reflect the users' opinions.
[src:developer-experience/usability] When written carefully and given to actual users who have experience with the product and knowledge of design, surveys provide useful feedback on the strong and weak areas of the usability of a design.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This is a very common method and often does not appear to be a survey, but just a warranty card.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It is often very difficult for designers to conduct usability tests with the exact system being designed.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Cost constraints, size, and design constraints usually lead the designer to creating a prototype of the system.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Instead of creating the complete final system, the designer may test different sections of the system, thus making several small models of each component of the system.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Prototyping is an attitude and an output, as it is a process for generating and reflecting on tangible ideas by allowing failure to occur early. prototyping helps people to see what could be of communicating a shared vision, and of giving shape to the future.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The types of usability prototypes may vary from using paper models, index cards, hand drawn models, or storyboards.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This tool kit is a wide library of methods that used the traditional programming language and it is primarily developed for computer programmers.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The code created for testing in the tool kit approach can be used in the final product.
[src:developer-experience/usability] However, to get the highest benefit from the tool, the user must be an expert programmer.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The two elements of this approach include a parts library and a method used for identifying the connection between the parts.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This approach can be used by almost anyone and it is a great asset for designers with repetitive tasks.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This approach is a combination of the tool kit approach and the part kit approach.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Both the dialogue designers and the programmers are able to interact with this prototyping tool.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Rapid prototyping is a method used in early stages of development to validate and refine the usability of a system.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It can be used to quickly and cheaply evaluate user-interface designs without the need for an expensive working model.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This can help remove hesitation to change the design, since it is implemented before any real programming begins.
[src:developer-experience/usability] One such method of rapid prototyping is paper prototyping.
[src:developer-experience/usability] These usability evaluation methods involve testing of subjects for the most quantitative data.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usually recorded on video, they provide task completion time and allow for observation of attitude.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Regardless to how carefully a system is designed, all theories must be tested using usability tests.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability tests involve typical users using the system (or product) in a realistic environment [see simulation].
[src:developer-experience/usability] Observation of the user's behavior, emotions, and difficulties while performing different tasks, often identify areas of improvement for the system.
[src:developer-experience/usability] While conducting usability tests, designers must use usability metrics to identify what it is they are going to measure, or the usability metrics.
[src:developer-experience/usability] These metrics are often variable, and change in conjunction with the scope and goals of the project.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The number of subjects being tested can also affect usability metrics, as it is often easier to focus on specific demographics.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Qualitative design phases, such as general usability (can the task be accomplished?), and user satisfaction are also typically done with smaller groups of subjects.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Using inexpensive prototypes on small user groups provides more detailed information, because of the more interactive atmosphere, and the designer's ability to focus more on the individual user.
[src:developer-experience/usability] As the designs become more complex, the testing must become more formalized.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Testing equipment will become more sophisticated and testing metrics become more quantitative.
[src:developer-experience/usability] With a more refined prototype, designers often test effectiveness, efficiency, and subjective satisfaction, by asking the user to complete various tasks.
[src:developer-experience/usability] These categories are measured by the percent that complete the task, how long it takes to complete the tasks, ratios of success to failure to complete the task, time spent on errors, the number of errors, rating scale of satisfactions, number of times user seems frustrated, etc.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Additional observations of the users give designers insight on navigation difficulties, controls, conceptual models, etc.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The ultimate goal of analyzing these metrics is to find/create a prototype design that users like and use to successfully perform given tasks.
[src:developer-experience/usability] After conducting usability tests, it is important for a designer to record what was observed, in addition to why such behavior occurred and modify the model according to the results.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Often it is quite difficult to distinguish the source of the design errors, and what the user did wrong.
[src:developer-experience/usability] However, effective usability tests will not generate a solution to the problems, but provide modified design guidelines for continued testing.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Additionally, this style of user testing also provides an opportunity to segment feedback by demographic, attitudinal and behavioral type.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The tests are carried out in the user's own environment (rather than labs) helping further simulate real-life scenario testing.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This approach also provides a vehicle to easily solicit feedback from users in remote areas.
[src:developer-experience/usability] There are two types, quantitative or qualitative.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Quantitative use large sample sized and task based surveys.
[src:developer-experience/usability] These types of studies are useful for validating suspected usability issues.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Qualitative studies are best used as exploratory research, in small sample sizes but frequent, even daily iterations.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The growth in mobile and associated platforms and services (e.g.: Mobile gaming has experienced 20x growth in 2010–2012) has generated a need for unmoderated remote usability testing on mobile devices, both for websites but especially for app interactions.
[src:developer-experience/usability] One methodology consists of shipping cameras and special camera holding fixtures to dedicated testers, and having them record the screens of the mobile smart-phone or tablet device, usually using an HD camera.
[src:developer-experience/usability] A drawback of this approach is that the finger movements of the respondent can obscure the view of the screen, in addition to the bias and logistical issues inherent in shipping special hardware to selected respondents.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The Think aloud protocol is a method of gathering data that is used in both usability and psychology studies.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It involves getting a user to verbalize their thought processes (i.e. expressing their opinions, thoughts, anticipations, and actions) as they perform a task or set of tasks.
[src:developer-experience/usability] As a widespread method of usability testing, think aloud provides the researchers with the ability to discover what user really think during task performance and completion.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Often an instructor is present to prompt the user into being more vocal as they work.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Similar to the Subjects-in-Tandem method, it is useful in pinpointing problems and is relatively simple to set up.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Additionally, it can provide insight into the user's attitude, which can not usually be discerned from a survey or questionnaire.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Rapid Iterative Testing and Evaluation (RITE) is an iterative usability method similar to traditional "discount" usability testing.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The tester and team must define a target population for testing, schedule participants to come into the lab, decide on how the users behaviors will be measured, construct a test script and have participants engage in a verbal protocol (e.g., think aloud).
[src:developer-experience/usability] However it differs from these methods in that it advocates that changes to the user interface are made as soon as a problem is identified and a solution is clear.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Sometimes this can occur after observing as few as 1 participant.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Once the data for a participant has been collected the usability engineer and team decide if they will be making any changes to the prototype prior to the next participant.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The changed interface is then tested with the remaining users.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Subjects-in-tandem (also called co-discovery) is the pairing of subjects in a usability test to gather important information on the ease of use of a product.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Subjects tend to discuss the tasks they have to accomplish out loud and through these discussions observers learn where the problem areas of a design are.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Component-based usability testing is an approach which aims to test the usability of elementary units of an interaction system, referred to as interaction components.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The approach includes component-specific quantitative measures based on user interaction recorded in log files, and component-based usability questionnaires.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Cognitive walkthrough is a method of evaluating the user interaction of a working prototype or final product.
[src:developer-experience/usability] It is used to evaluate the system's ease of learning.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Cognitive walkthrough is useful to understand the user's thought processes and decision making when interacting with a system, specially for first-time or infrequent users.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Benchmarking creates standardized test materials for a specific type of design.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Four key characteristics are considered when establishing a benchmark: time to do the core task, time to fix errors, time to learn applications, and the functionality of the system.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Once there is a benchmark, other designs can be compared to it to determine the usability of the system.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Many of the common objectives of usability studies, such as trying to understand user behavior or exploring alternative designs, must be put aside.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Unlike many other usability methods or types of labs studies, benchmark studies more closely resemble true experimental psychology lab studies, with greater attention to detail on methodology, study protocol and data analysis.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Meta-analysis is a statistical procedure to combine results across studies to integrate the findings.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This phrase was coined in 1976 as a quantitative literature review.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This type of evaluation is very powerful for determining the usability of a device because it combines multiple studies to provide very accurate quantitative support.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Personas are fictitious characters created to represent a site or product's different user types and their associated demographics and technographics.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Alan Cooper introduced the concept of using personas as a part of interactive design in 1998 in his book *The Inmates Are Running the Asylum*, but had used this concept since as early as 1975.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Personas are a usability evaluation method that can be used at various design stages.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The most typical time to create personas is at the beginning of designing so that designers have a tangible idea of who the users of their product will be.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Personas are the archetypes that represent actual groups of users and their needs, which can be a general description of person, context, or usage scenario.
[src:developer-experience/usability] This technique turns marketing data on target user population into a few physical concepts of users to create empathy among the design team, with the final aim of tailoring a product more closely to how the personas will use it.
[src:developer-experience/usability] To gather the marketing data that personas require, several tools can be used, including online surveys, web analytics, customer feedback forms, and usability tests, and interviews with customer-service representatives.
[src:developer-experience/usability] An increase in usability generally positively affects several facets of a company's output quality.
[src:developer-experience/usability] By working to improve said factors, corporations can achieve their goals of increased output at lower costs, while potentially creating optimal levels of customer satisfaction.
[src:developer-experience/usability] There are numerous reasons why each of these factors correlates to overall improvement.
[src:developer-experience/usability] For example, making software user interfaces easier to understand reduces the need for extensive training.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The improved interface tends to lower the time needed to perform tasks, and so would both raise the productivity levels for employees and reduce development time (and thus costs).
[src:developer-experience/usability] Each of the aforementioned factors are not mutually exclusive; rather they should be understood to work in conjunction to form the overall workplace environment.
[src:developer-experience/usability] In the 2010s, usability is recognized as an important software quality attribute, earning its place among more traditional attributes such as performance, robustness and aesthetic appearance.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Various academic programs focus on usability.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Several usability consultancy companies have emerged, and traditional consultancy and design firms offer similar services.
[src:developer-experience/usability] There is some resistance to integrating usability work in organisations.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability is seen as a vague concept, it is difficult to measure and other areas are prioritised when IT projects run out of time or money.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Usability practitioners are sometimes trained as industrial engineers, psychologists, kinesiologists, systems design engineers, or with a degree in information architecture, information or library science, or Human-Computer Interaction (HCI).
[src:developer-experience/usability] More often though they are people who are trained in specific applied fields who have taken on a usability focus within their organization.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Anyone who aims to make tools easier to use and more effective for their desired function within the context of work or everyday living can benefit from studying usability principles and guidelines.
[src:developer-experience/usability] For those seeking to extend their training, the User Experience Professionals' Association offers online resources, reference lists, courses, conferences, and local chapter meetings.
[src:developer-experience/usability] The UXPA also sponsors World Usability Day each November.
[src:developer-experience/usability] Related professional organizations include the Human Factors and Ergonomics Society (HFES) and the Association for Computing Machinery's special interest groups in Computer Human Interaction (SIGCHI), Design of Communication (SIGDOC) and Computer Graphics and Interactive Techniques (SIGGRAPH).
[src:developer-experience/usability] The Society for Technical Communication also has a special interest group on Usability and User Experience (UUX).
[src:developer-experience/usability] They publish a quarterly newsletter called *Usability Interface*.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] According to Nielsen Norman Group, 'user experience' includes all the aspects of the interaction between the end-user with the company, its services, and its products.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The international standard on *ergonomics of human-system interaction*, ISO 9241, defines user experience as a "user's perceptions and responses that result from the use and/or anticipated use of a system, product or service".
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] According to the ISO definition, user experience includes all the users' emotions, beliefs, preferences, perceptions, physical and psychological responses, behaviors, and accomplishments that occur before, during, and after use.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The ISO also lists three factors that influence user experience: the system, the user, and the context of use.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Note 3 of the standard hints that usability addresses aspects of user experience, e.g., "usability criteria can be used to assess aspects of user experience".
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The standard does not go further in clarifying the relation between user experience and usability.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Clearly, the two are overlapping concepts, with usability including pragmatic aspects (getting a task done) and user experience focusing on users' feelings stemming from both pragmatic and hedonic aspects of the system.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Many practitioners use the terms interchangeably.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The term "usability" pre-dates the term "user experience".
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Part of the reason the terms are often used interchangeably is that, as a practical matter, a user will, at a minimum, require sufficient usability to accomplish a task, while the feelings of the user may be less important, even to the user themselves.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Since usability is about getting a task done, aspects of user experience like information architecture and user interface can help or hinder a user's experience.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] If a website has "bad" information architecture and a user has a difficult time finding what they are looking for, then the user will not have an effective, efficient, and satisfying search.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] In addition to the ISO standard, there exist several other definitions for user experience.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Some of them have been studied by various researchers.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Early developments in user experience can be traced back to the Machine Age, which includes the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Frederick Winslow Taylor and Henry Ford explored ways to make human labor more efficient and productive.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Taylor's research into the efficiency of interactions between workers and their tools is the earliest example that resembles today's user experience fundamentals.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The term *user experience* was brought to wider knowledge by Donald Norman in the mid-1990s.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] He never intended the term "user experience" to be applied only to the affective aspects of usage.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] A review of his earlier work suggests that the term "user experience" was used to signal a shift to include affective factors, along with the pre-requisite behavioral concerns, which had been traditionally considered in the field.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Many usability practitioners continue to research and attend to affective factors associated with end-users, and have been doing so for years, long before the term "user experience" was introduced in the mid-1990s.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] In an interview in 2007, Norman discusses the widespread use of the term "user experience" and its imprecise meaning as a consequence thereof.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] In website design, it was important to combine the interests of different stakeholders: marketing, branding, visual design, and usability.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Marketing and branding people needed to enter the interactive world where usability was important.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Usability people needed to take marketing, branding, and aesthetic needs into account when designing websites.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] User experience provided a platform to cover the interests of all stakeholders: making websites easy to use, valuable, and effective for visitors.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] This is why several early user experience publications focus on website user experience.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The field of user experience represents an expansion and extension of the field of usability to include the holistic perspective of how a person feels about using a system.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The focus is on pleasure and value as well as on performance.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The exact definition, framework, and elements of user experience are still evolving.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] User experience of an interactive product or a website is usually measured by a number of methods, including questionnaires, focus groups, observed usability tests, user journey mapping and other methods.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] A freely available questionnaire (available in several languages) is the User Experience Questionnaire (UEQ).
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The development and validation of this questionnaire is described in a computer science essay published in 2008.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Higher levels of user experience have been linked to increased effectiveness of digital health interventions targeting improvements in physical activity, nutrition, mental health and smoking.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Google Ngram Viewer shows wide use of the term starting in the 1930s.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] "He suggested that more follow-up in the field would be welcomed by the user, and would be a means of incorporating the results of the user's experience into the design of new machines." Use of the term in relation to computer software also pre-dates Norman.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Many factors can influence a user's experience with a system.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] To address the variety, factors influencing user experience have been classified into three main categories: the user's state and previous experience, system properties, and the usage context (situation).
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Understanding representative users, working environments, interactions, and emotional reactions helps in designing the system during User experience design.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The overall user experience is not simply a sum of smaller interaction experiences, because some experiences are more salient than others.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Overall user experience is also influenced by factors outside the actual interaction episode: brand, pricing, friends' opinions, reports in the media, etc.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] One branch of user experience research focuses on emotions.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] This includes momentary experiences during interaction: designing effective interaction and evaluating emotions.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Another branch is interested in understanding the long-term relationship between user experience and product appreciation.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] The industry sees a good overall user experience with a company's products as critical for securing brand loyalty and enhancing the growth of the customer base.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] All temporal levels of user experience (momentary, episodic, and long-term) are important, but the methods to design and evaluate these levels can be very different.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] While user experience has become an essential part of design and product development, it has also attracted criticism and ethical scrutiny.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Focusing on user satisfaction and business goals may lead to harmful design choices, unintentional accessibility gaps, or user manipulation.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] These conflicts suggest that UX has room to become a more responsible and inclusive practice.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] One major critique of UX is the conflict between designing for user benefit and designing for business objectives.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] UX decisions are often shaped by financial incentives rather than users’ well-being.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] This leads to design choices that prioritize growth over ethics, for example, features that encourage excessive screen time, collect unnecessary personal data (also known as *privacy zuckering*), or make it difficult for users to unsubscribe from services (also known as *forced continuity*).
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] While trying to increase profits, it may actually increase economic harm and reduce market efficiency.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Critics argue that such practices compromise the foundational goal of UX, which is to improve the user's experience, not exploit it.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Companies can be held accountable for their design choices by prioritizing user interests.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] For instance, ensuring price transparency helps users make informed decisions.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Organizations can also align design decisions with user well-being by evaluating qualitative outcomes, like how a product contributes to users’ happiness or mental health, instead of relying solely on engagement metrics.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] By making business success dependent on user trust and satisfaction, rather than engagement metrics alone, organizations can create sustainable products that support both profitability and user well-being.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Another major ethical concern in UX is the use of dark patterns, interface designs that intentionally mislead or manipulate users into taking actions they might not otherwise choose.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Examples include use of checkboxes to opt out rather than opt in (double negatives), confusing cancellation processes, or “confirm” buttons that lead to unintended purchases.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Scholars from Princeton and Purdue University have argued that dark patterns represent a misuse of UX principles, using psychological insights and interface design against user interests.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] One proposed solution to the problem of dark patterns is to focus on how to distinguish manipulative patterns from legitimate persuasion.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] For example, researchers at Princeton suggest using guidelines to evaluate when a design crosses the line into manipulation.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Researchers from Purdue University instead argue that ethical awareness cannot rely solely on codes of conduct but should instead focus on the designer’s intent, judgment, and ongoing responsibility.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Another area of criticism concerns accessibility and inclusivity in UX design.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Although improving usability is a central aim of UX, many products and services continue to overlook the needs of people with disabilities, older users, or those from different cultural and linguistic backgrounds.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] This exclusion can occur due to implicit bias in design teams, lack of diverse user testing, or assumptions about “average” users.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] To address these gaps, experts recommend adopting inclusive design principles throughout the development process.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] This includes conducting accessibility audits, following the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG), and involving users with disabilities in usability testing to ensure products meet real-world needs.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Expanding user research to include diverse groups can also uncover assumptions and biases early.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Additionally, ongoing education about unconscious bias for design teams can help create products that reflect a broader range of user experiences.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] Developer experience (DX) is a user experience from a developer's point of view.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] It is defined by the tools, processes, and software that a developer uses when interacting with a product or system while in the process of producing another one, such as in software development.
[src:developer-experience/user-experience] DX has had increased attention paid to it, especially in businesses that primarily offer software as a service to other businesses, where ease of use is a key differentiator in the market.
[src:developer-experience/what-is-backstage] Backstage is an open source framework for building developer portals.
[src:developer-experience/what-is-backstage] Powered by a centralized software catalog, Backstage restores order to your microservices and infrastructure and enables your product teams to ship high-quality code quickly — without compromising autonomy.
[src:developer-experience/what-is-backstage] Backstage unifies all your infrastructure tooling, services, and documentation to create a streamlined development environment from end to end.
[src:developer-experience/what-is-backstage] Backstage is a CNCF Incubation project after graduating from Sandbox.
[src:developer-experience/what-is-backstage] If you have questions or want support, please join our Discord chatroom.
